While it's still hot, pour the melted chocolate into individual candy molds. Molds come in all sorts of shapes and sizes, and can be found at kitchen supply stores. Fill the molds to their rims. If necessary, use the back of a spoon to smooth the chocolate into the corners. If you don't have candy molds, get creative and make your own. Use mini muffin tins, small paper cups, shot glasses, or another type of container as molds. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2b/Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2b/Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

To help the chocolate settle, you can lift it a few inches above the counter and let it drop. This removes air bubbles and smooths out the chocolate. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/68/Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/68/Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

To make filled chocolates, fill the molds halfway, then spoon a bit of caramel, peanut butter, or another filling in the center of the chocolate. Pour more chocolate on top of the filling to fill the mold to the top. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/90/Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/90/Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-759px-Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Sprinkle the chocolate with sprinkles or other decorations if you wish. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b7/Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-3Bullet4.jpg/v4-459px-Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-3Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b7/Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-3Bullet4.jpg/v4-759px-Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-3Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Pour it into a baking pan or cake pan and let it stand on the counter until the mixture thickens a bit. Stir it once more, then cover it with plastic wrap and place it in the refrigerator. Let the chocolate cool for 2 hours. Check to make sure the chocolate has thoroughly cooled before moving on to the next step. It will be much more difficult to handle if it's still warm. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/93/Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-9Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-9Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/93/Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-9Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-9Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

It's fine to melt the chocolate and chill it overnight if you want to make truffles the next day. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4a/Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-9Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-9Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4a/Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-9Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-9Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use a small ice cream scoop or a rounded teaspoon to scoop chocolate from the pan. Shape it into a ball with your hands, working quickly so the chocolate doesn't melt. Place the chocolate truffle on a baking sheet lined with parchment or wax paper, to keep it from sticking. Repeat with the remaining chocolate, taking care to make the truffles equal in size. If the chocolate starts melting as you handle it, try coating your hands in cocoa powder, or running them under cool water and thoroughly drying them before continuing. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ed/Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-10Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-10Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ed/Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-10Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-10Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

You can also place the chocolate back in the refrigerator to cool it down as necessary. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ee/Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-10Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-10Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ee/Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-10Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Make-Home-Made-Chocolates-Step-10Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
